on gas, and nuclear devices, as well as the connection between bioattacks and natural disease pandemics. Avery emphasizes the crucially important activities of Canadian biodefence scientists – beginning with Nobel Laureate Frederick Banting – at both the national level and through cooperative projects within the framework of an elaborate alliance system.Delving into history through a rich collection of declassified documents, Pathogens for War also devotes several chapters to the contemporary challenges of bioterrorism and disease pandemics from both national and international perspectives. As such, readers will not only learn about Canada’s secret involvement with biological warfare, but will also gain new insights into current debates about the peril of bioweapons – one of today’s greatest threats to world peace.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBiological weaponszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aBioterrorismzCanadaxPreventionxHistoryy20th century. 0aCommunicable diseaseszCanadaxPreventionxHistoryy20th century. 0aLife scientistszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aHISTORY / Military / Canada.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266498240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442664982423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442664982.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK